of RxJS.

buffer
description:
buffers the incoming observable values until the passed `closingNotifier` emits a value, at which point
it emits the buffer on the returned observable and starts a new buffer internally, awaiting the
next time `closingNotifier` emits

unknown.tagValue: {Observable<T[]>} an observable of buffers, which are arrays of values

params.name: closingNotifier
params.description: an observable, that signals the buffer to be emitted from the returned observable

return.description: an observable of buffers, which are arrays of values

name: es6/operators/bufferCount.js
bufferCount
description:
buffers a number of values from the source observable by `bufferSize` then emits the buffer and clears it, and starts a
new buffer each `startBufferEvery` values. If `startBufferEvery` is not provided or is `null`, then new buffers are
started immediately at the start of the source and when each buffer closes and is emitted.

unknown.tagValue: {Observable<T[]>} an observable of arrays of buffered values.

params.name: bufferSize
params.description: the maximum size of the buffer emitted.

params.name: startBufferEvery
params.description:
optional interval at which to start a new buffer. (e.g. if `startBufferEvery` is `2`,asdf then a
  new buffer will be started on every other value from the source.) A new buffer is started at the beginning of the source by default.

return.description: an observable of arrays of buffered values.

name: es6/operators/bufferTime.js
bufferTime

unknown.tagValue: {Observable<T[]>} an observable of arrays of buffered values.

params.name: the
params.description: amount of time to fill each buffer for before emitting them and clearing them.

params.name: bufferCreationInterval
params.description: the interval at which to start new buffers.

params.name: scheduler

(optional, defaults to `nextTick` scheduler) The scheduler on which to schedule the
 intervals that determine buffer boundaries.

return.description: an observable of arrays of buffered values.

name: es6/operators/combineAll.js
combineAll
description:
Takes an Observable of Observables, and collects all observables from it. Once the outer observable
completes, it subscribes to all collected observables and "combines" their values, such that:
 - every time an observable emits, the returned observable emits
 - when the returned observable emits, it emits all of the most recent values by:
   - if a `project` function is provided, it is called with each recent value from each observable in whatever order they arrived,
     and the result of the `project` function is what is emitted by the returned observable
   - if there is no `project` function, an array of all of the most recent values is emitted by the returned observable.

unknown.tagValue: {Observable} an observable of projected results or arrays of recent values.

params.name: project
params.description:
an optional function to map the most recent values from each observable into a new result. Takes each of the
  most recent values from each collected observable as arguments, in order.

return.description: an observable of projected results or arrays of recent values.

name: es6/operators/combineLatest-static.js
combineLatest
description:
Combines the values from observables passed as arguments. This is done by subscribing
to each observable, in order, and collecting an array of each of the most recent values any time any of the observables
emits, then either taking that array and passing it as arguments to an option `project` function and emitting the return
value of that, or just emitting the array of recent values directly if there is no `project` function.

unknown.tagValue:
{Observable} an observable of other projected values from the most recent values from each observable, or an array of each of
the most recent values from each observable.

params.name: observables
params.description: the observables to combine

params.name: project
params.description: an optional function to project the values from the combined recent values into a new value for emission.

return.description:
an observable of other projected values from the most recent values from each observable, or an array of each of
the most recent values from each observable.

name: es6/operators/concat.js
concat
description:
Joins this observable with multiple other observables by subscribing to them one at a time, starting with the source,
and merging their results into the returned observable. Will wait for each observable to complete before moving
on to the next.

unknown.tagValue: {...Observable} the observables to concatenate
{Scheduler} [scheduler] an optional scheduler to schedule each observable subscription on.

return.description: All values of each passed observable merged into a single observable, in order, in serial fashion.

name: es6/operators/concatAll.js
concatAll
description:
Joins every Observable emitted by the source (an Observable of Observables), in a serial
fashion. Subscribing to each one only when the previous one has completed, and merging
all of their values into the returned observable.

__Warning:__ If the source Observable emits Observables quickly and endlessly, and the
Observables it emits generally complete slower than the source emits, you can run into
memory issues as the incoming observables collect in an unbounded buffer.

unknown.tagValue: {Observable} an observable of values merged from the incoming observables.

return.description: an observable of values merged from the incoming observables.

name: es6/operators/concatMap.js
content:
import { MergeMapOperator } from './mergeMap-support';
/**
 * Maps values from the source observable into new Observables, then merges them in a serialized fashion,
 * waiting for each one to complete before merging the next.
 *
 * __Warning:__ if incoming values arrive endlessly and faster than the observables they're being mapped
 * to can complete, it will result in memory issues as created observables amass in an unbounded buffer
 * waiting for their turn to be subscribed to.
 *
 * @param {function} project a function to map incoming values into Observables to be concatenated. accepts
 * the `value` and the `index` as arguments.
 * @param {function} [projectResult] an optional result selector that is applied to values before they're
 * merged into the returned observable. The arguments passed to this function are:
 * - `outerValue`: the value that came from the source
 * - `innerValue`: the value that came from the projected Observable
 * - `outerIndex`: the "index" of the value that came from the source
 * - `innerIndex`: the "index" of the value from the projected Observable
 * @returns {Observable} an observable of values merged from the projected Observables as they were subscribed to,
 * one at a time. Optionally, these values may have been projected from a passed `projectResult` argument.
 */
export default function concatMap(project, projectResult) {
    return this.lift(new MergeMapOperator(project, projectResult, 1));
}

name: concatMap
description:
Maps values from the source observable into new Observables, then merges them in a serialized fashion,
waiting for each one to complete before merging the next.

__Warning:__ if incoming values arrive endlessly and faster than the observables they're being mapped
to can complete, it will result in memory issues as created observables amass in an unbounded buffer
waiting for their turn to be subscribed to.

unknown.tagValue:
{Observable} an observable of values merged from the projected Observables as they were subscribed to,
one at a time. Optionally, these values may have been projected from a passed `projectResult` argument.

params.name: project
params.description:
a function to map incoming values into Observables to be concatenated. accepts
the `value` and the `index` as arguments.

params.name: projectResult
params.description:
an optional result selector that is applied to values before they're
merged into the returned observable. The arguments passed to this function are:
- `outerValue`: the value that came from the source
- `innerValue`: the value that came from the projected Observable
- `outerIndex`: the "index" of the value that came from the source
- `innerIndex`: the "index" of the value from the projected Observable

return.description:
an observable of values merged from the projected Observables as they were subscribed to,
one at a time. Optionally, these values may have been projected from a passed `projectResult` argument.

name: es6/operators/concatMapTo.js
content:
import { MergeMapToOperator } from './mergeMapTo-support';
/**
 * Maps values from the source to a specific observable, and merges them together in a serialized fashion.
 *
 * @param {Observable} observable the observable to map each source value to
 * @param {function} [projectResult] an optional result selector that is applied to values before they're
 * merged into the returned observable. The arguments passed to this function are:
 * - `outerValue`: the value that came from the source
 * - `innerValue`: the value that came from the projected Observable
 * - `outerIndex`: the "index" of the value that came from the source
 * - `innerIndex`: the "index" of the value from the projected Observable
 * @returns {Observable} an observable of values merged together by joining the passed observable
 * with itself, one after the other, for each value emitted from the source.
 */
export default function concatMapTo(observable, projectResult) {
    return this.lift(new MergeMapToOperator(observable, projectResult, 1));
}

name: concatMapTo
description: Maps values from the source to a specific observable, and merges them together in a serialized fashion.

unknown.tagValue:
{Observable} an observable of values merged together by joining the passed observable
with itself, one after the other, for each value emitted from the source.

params.name: observable
params.description: the observable to map each source value to

params.name: projectResult
params.description:
an optional result selector that is applied to values before they're
merged into the returned observable. The arguments passed to this function are:
- `outerValue`: the value that came from the source
- `innerValue`: the value that came from the projected Observable
- `outerIndex`: the "index" of the value that came from the source
- `innerIndex`: the "index" of the value from the projected Observable

return.description:
an observable of values merged together by joining the passed observable
with itself, one after the other, for each value emitted from the source.

name: es6/operators/count.js
count
description:
Returns an observable of a single number that represents the number of items that either:
Match a provided predicate function, _or_ if a predicate is not provided, the number
represents the total count of all items in the source observable. The count is emitted
by the returned observable when the source observable completes.

unknown.tagValue:
{Observable} an observable of one number that represents the count as described
above

params.name: predicate
params.description:
a boolean function to select what values are to be counted.
it is provided with arguments of:
  - `value`: the value from the source observable
  - `index`: the "index" of the value from the source observable
  - `source`: the source observable instance itself.

params.name: thisArg
params.description: the optional `this` context to use in the `predicate` function

return.description:
an observable of one number that represents the count as described
above

unknown.tagValue:
merges each value from an observable with the latest values from the other passed observables.
All observables must emit at least one value before the resulting observable will emit

#### example
```
A.withLatestFrom(B, C)

 A:     ----a-----------------b---------------c-----------|
 B:     ---d----------------e--------------f---------|
 C:     --x----------------y-------------z-------------|
result: ---([a,d,x])---------([b,e,y])--------([c,f,z])---|
```

params.name: observables
params.description: the observables to get the latest values from.

params.name: project
params.description:
optional projection function for merging values together. Receives all values in order
 of observables passed. (e.g. `a.withLatestFrom(b, c, (a1, b1, c1) => a1 + b1 + c1)`). If this is not passed, arrays
 will be returned.
